{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|うめ}}

{{IPAfont|⟨me<sub>2</sub>⟩}} → *{{IPAchar|/mːəɨ/}} → {{IPAfont|⟨mume<sub>2</sub>⟩}} → {{IPAfont|⟨ume<sub>2</sub>⟩}} → *{{IPAchar|/uməɨ/}} → {{IPAchar|/ume/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=うめ|-}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR"/><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref> Found already in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' with the ''ume'' reading, completed some time after 759 {{CE}}.<ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|5|822}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man5Yos.html#822 here]</ref>

Probably ultimately from {{der|ja|ltc|sort=うめ|-}} {{ltc-l|梅}},<ref name="DJR"/><ref name="DJS"/> with the borrowed ''me'' reading gaining a pronounced kind of initial ''m-'' sound, perhaps realized as *''mme''. The phonetic spelling was often rendered as {{m|ja||むめ|tr=*mme, mume}} from the {{w|Heian period}},<ref name="KDJ"/><ref name="DJS"/> with *''mme''/''mume'' and ''ume'' apparently existing in free variation. The reading eventually settled on {{m|ja||うめ|tr=ume}}. Compare the similar pattern of phonetic shift for {{m|ja|馬|tr=ma → *mma → muma → uma||[[horse]]}}, from {{cog|ltc|-}} {{ltc-l|馬}}.

